    "author_association": "CONTRIBUTOR",
    "body": "### Neovim version (nvim -v)\n\n0.6.0 commit 3f526feebfe6\n\n### Vim (not Nvim) behaves the same?\n\nno\n\n### Operating system/version\n\nmacOS (any recent or all versions)\n\n### Terminal name/version\n\nApple's Terminal.app\n\n### $TERM environment variable\n\nxterm-256color\n\n### Installation\n\nbuild from repo\n\n### How to reproduce the issue\n\nrun 'make test' in the neovim top direcotry.\n\n### Expected behavior\n\nNo user files are removed.\n\n### Actual behavior\n\nPre-existing corefiles in /cores are removed.\r\n\r\nOn macOS core files are saved in the directory /cores. When I run 'make test' for nvim, if there is already core file(s) in /cores (not of nvim but of the program I'm currently working on), check_cores() in test/helpers.lua starts debugger (lldb) and shows a back trace of the core(s). This is quite misleading. Moreover, if I hit 'q' to quit the debugger the core file is **removed**!! In my opinion this is totally unacceptable. Some coredumps are not easy to reproduce.\r\n\r\nShould any users read test/README.md carefully _before_ running 'make test'?\r\n\r\nI believe check_cores() should be activated only if user explicitly asked for it (at least on macOS). Or modify check_cores() so that pre-existing core files are ignored (and not removed).\r\n\r\nOr rename the make target 'test' to 'test-for-ci' or such if the test is intended to be used only by CI and not by human users.",
    "closed_at": null,
    "closed_by": null,
